<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-22</title>
<p><b>Thesis.</b> This week’s four deep threads point to the same bottleneck: embodied foundation models do not lack data or generative capacity; they lack a <b>change-and-skill memory layer</b> that survives occlusion, spans embodiments, and can be reused cheaply. HumanScale shows that the pretraining substrate should prioritize coverage over embodiment alignment. ImageWAM shows the action model does not need decoded video. WRBench diagnoses why current video models fail when the view returns: they remember where to look but not what changed. RATS shows that self-directed play can build a reusable code skill library. Read together, the papers argue the field is moving from “generate plausible futures” to “remember the right abstractions.”</p>
<callout emoji="❗" background-color="light-yellow" border-color="yellow"><p><b>The non-obvious claim:</b> HumanScale’s 90% OOD real-robot success and ImageWAM’s 6× FLOP reduction are not independent wins. They describe the two ends of a plausible cheap-and-general pipeline: pretrain on nearly-free egocentric video, then deploy with a transformation-aware action expert that never decodes video. The missing piece—the piece none of the four papers fully solves—is whether that pipeline can maintain a persistent world state when the camera looks away.</p></callout>
<h1>What this run actually learned</h1>
<ol><li><b>Robot data saturates structurally; egocentric video does not.</b> HumanScale finds that at matched 5,000-hour scale, real-robot pretraining barely improves on unseen tasks while egocentric video follows a clean log-linear law. The reason is not better actions—it is lower redundancy: an hour of teleoperation contains ~5.6× fewer trajectories than an hour of egocentric video and is confined to a fixed workstation manifold.</li>
<li><b>“Generate video” is the wrong inference objective for action.</b> ImageWAM’s released code shows that the action expert can be conditioned on a single image-editing cache instead of 16 decoded future frames, with comparable task success. This means the expensive part of video-WAM inference is mostly a rendering side effect, not a reasoning necessity.</li>
<li><b>Current video world models are view-conditioned renderers, not state simulators.</b> WRBench’s six-dimensional diagnosis shows that models can execute camera motion and render plausible visible frames yet fail to preserve event endpoints after a hidden interval. Scaling Wan 2.1 from 1.3B to 14B improves visual quality but lowers conditional re-observed-state consistency, proving the failure is not a pixel-budget problem.</li>
<li><b>Play is useful when it produces reusable structure, not just more trials.</b> RATS’s compute-matched ablation is the telling result: spending the same 50-iteration token budget on extra test-time retries gains +2.8 pp, while spending it on curiosity-driven play gains +9.1 pp under the same test-time agent. The value is in named, verifiable code skills, not in additional inference.</li>
<li><b>The reproducibility gradient is steep.</b> ImageWAM and RATS ship runnable code and configs. WRBench releases data manifests and evaluation code. HumanScale’s strongest claim currently rests on a repository landing page with no model, pipeline, or checkpoints. That asymmetry should affect how much we update our priors for each result.</li></ol>
<h1>Theme 1: Pretraining substrates — coverage beats alignment at scale</h1>
<p>The conventional recipe is to collect more real-robot data because it is kinematically aligned. HumanScale turns that argument on its head: for pretraining, the marginal value of a wider distribution outweighs the marginal value of embodiment alignment. The paper’s controlled design makes this claim unusually sharp.</p>
